Here's a multi-form question based on the provided LaTeX documentation:

Question: In a LaTeX document, you want to change all section headings to a sans-serif font while keeping the main text in a serif font. Which of the following code snippets would correctly achieve this?

A) \usepackage{sectsty}
   \begin{document}
   \allsectionsfont{\rmfamily}
   [...]
   \end{document}

B) \usepackage{sectsty}
   \begin{document}
   \allsectionsfont{\sffamily}
   [...]
   \end{document}

C) \usepackage{titlesec}
   \begin{document}
   \titleformat*{\section}{\sffamily}
   [...]
   \end{document}

D) \usepackage{fontspec}
   \begin{document}
   \setmainfont{Times New Roman}
   \setsansfont{Arial}
   [...]
   \end{document}

Correct Answer: B

Explanation: Option B is the correct answer because it uses the `sectsty` package and the `\allsectionsfont` command with `\sffamily` to set all section headings to sans-serif. Option A incorrectly uses `\rmfamily` which would set headings to serif. Option C uses `titlesec`, which can change section formatting but requires more complex syntax to affect all heading levels. Option D changes the document's main fonts but doesn't specifically target section headings.
